\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concept of cardinality is important in modern mathematics in general
 and in analysis in particular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Cardinality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be sets.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 have the same 
\emph on
cardinality
\emph default
 when there exists a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon A\mapsto B$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|$
\end_inset

 the equivalence class of all sets with the same cardinality as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and we simply call 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|$
\end_inset

 the cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same cardinality as the empty set iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 itself is the empty set, written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|\coloneqq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same cardinality as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,\dots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We then write 
\begin_inset Formula $A\coloneqq n.$
\end_inset

 In this case we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
finite, 
\emph default
otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is of infinite cardinality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|A\right|\leq\left|B\right|
\]

\end_inset

if there exists an injection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|<\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|=\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
Cantor-Bernstein-Schröder theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|=\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\iff$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|\leq\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|\geq\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|=\left|\mathbb{N}\right|$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
countably infinite
\emph default
, If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is finite or countably infinite, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
countable, 
\emph default
otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
uncountable
\emph default
.
 The cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is denotd by 
\begin_inset Formula $\aleph_{0}$
\end_inset

 (aleph-naught).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition*
A set is infinite iff it is in one-to-one correspondence with a proper subset
 of itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is a countably infinite set, the set of rational numbers is countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is countable/finite, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is countable/finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|<\left|\mathbb{N}\right|$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
Cantor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|A\right|<\left|\mathscr{P}\left(A\right)\right|
\]

\end_inset

In particular, there exists no surjection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Real Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take an approach that assumes a set with the correct properties exists.
 We need to start with the definitions of those properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Basic properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An ordered set is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, together with a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 s.t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
i.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in S$
\end_inset

, exactly one of 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y<x$
\end_inset

 holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
ii.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y<z$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x<z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
the set of rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is an ordered set by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x$
\end_inset

 is a positve rational number.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 are ordered sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subset S$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an ordered set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
i.
 If there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq b\,\forall x\in E$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is bounded above and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
ii.
 if there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq b\,\forall x\in E$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is bounded below and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a lower bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
iii.
 If there exists an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is any upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\leq b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 is called the least upper bound or the 
\emph on
supremum 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, denoted by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup E\coloneqq b_{o}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
iiii.
 Similarly, if there exists an lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{o}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 whenver 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is any lower bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}\geq b$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}$
\end_inset

 is called the greatest lower bound or the infimum of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, denoted by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\inf E\coloneqq b_{o}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
When a set is both bounded above and bounded below, we simply say it is
 
\emph on
bounded
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Supremum (or infimum) is automatically unique if it exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
An ordered set has the 
\emph on
completeness property
\emph default
 
\emph on
(least-upper-bound property) 
\emph default
if every nonempty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subset S$
\end_inset

 that is bounded above has a supremum, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup E\in S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
e.g.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 of rational numbers does not have this completeness property.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 does not have the completeness property is one of the most important reasons
 why we work with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 in analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We require real numbers to have many algebraic properties.
 In particular, we require that they are a field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
field
\emph default
 if it has two operations defined on it, addition 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y$
\end_inset

 and multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 , and if it satisfies the following axioms: closed under addition and multiplic
ation, commutativity, associativity, identity, inverse, distributivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(A1) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F,y\in F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(A2) (commutativity of addition) 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=y+x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(A3) (associativity of addtion) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x+y\right)+z=x+\left(y+z\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(A4) There exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in F$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $0+x=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(A5) For every element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset

 there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $-x\in F$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\left(-x\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(M1) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(M2) (commutativity of multiplication) 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=yx$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(M3) (associativity of multiplication) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(xy\right)z=x\left(yz\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(M4) There exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\neq0$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $1x=x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(M5) For every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in F$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

 there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x\in F$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(1/x\right)=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(D) (distributive law) 
\begin_inset Formula $x\left(y+z\right)=xy+xz$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 of rational numbers is a field.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is not a field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is said to be an ordered field if 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is also an ordered set s.t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(i) For 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z\in F,x<y$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+z<y+z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(ii) For 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in F,x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y>0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $xy>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
The rational numbers with the standard ordering is an ordered field.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 of complex numbers is not an ordered field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be an ordered field and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z,w\in F$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(i) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $-x<0$
\end_inset

 and vice versa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(ii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y<z$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy<xz$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y<z$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy>xz$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(iv) If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}>0$
