\begin_layout Section
Connected Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the main features of an interval in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is that is it connected.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 we usually study functions on intervals, and in more general metric spaces
 we usually study functions on connected sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A nonempty metric space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,d\right)$
\end_inset

 is connected if the only subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that are both open and closed (so-called clopen subsets) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 itself.
 If a nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,d\right)$
\end_inset

 is not connected we say it is disconnected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, a nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is connected if whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X_{1}\cup X_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\cap X_{2}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are open, then either 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X,d\right)$
\end_inset

 be a metric space.
 A nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subset X$
\end_inset

 is disconnected iff there exist open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\cap S=\emptyset,U_{1}\cap S\neq\emptyset,U_{2}\cap S\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 (disjoint and nonempty) and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left(U_{1}\cap S\right)\cup\left(U_{2}\cap S\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
A nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is connected iff it is an interval or a single point.
\end_layout

